  "text": "# Firefox CSP Enforcement Infrastructure Audit\n\nThis audit identified the core CSP (Content Security Policy) enforcement infrastructure in Firefox's `dom/security/` directory.\n\n## Key Files Identified\n\n### 1. CSP Parser (`dom/security/nsCSPParser.h` and `.cpp`)\nThe `nsCSPParser` class is the main CSP directive parser. It parses CSP policy strings according to the CSP specification, tokenizing directives and sources. The public entry point is the static method `nsCSPParser::parseContentSecurityPolicy()` which converts a policy string into an `nsCSPPolicy` object.\n\n### 2. CSP Context (`dom/security/nsCSPContext.h` and `.cpp`)\nThe `nsCSPContext` class implements the `nsIContentSecurityPolicy` XPCOM interface and serves as the main CSP context that holds and manages policies. It implements key methods like:\n- `ShouldLoad()` - Entry point for content policy checks\n- `permitsInternal()` - Core permission checking logic\n- `AsyncReportViolation()` - Violation reporting infrastructure\n- `ReportInlineViolation()` - Specific handler for inline script/style violations\n\n### 3. CSP Utilities (`dom/security/nsCSPUtils.h` and `.cpp`)\nThis file contains utility classes and functions for CSP enforcement:\n- `nsCSPBaseSrc` - Base class for CSP sources with the `permits()` and `allows()` methods\n- `nsCSPKeywordSrc`, `nsCSPNonceSrc`, `nsCSPHashSrc` - Specific source types with `allows()` implementations\n- `nsCSPDirective` - Represents a CSP directive\n- `nsCSPPolicy` - Represents a complete CSP policy\n- Logging functions like `CSP_LogLocalizedStr()`\n\n### 4. XPCOM Interface (`dom/interfaces/security/nsIContentSecurityPolicy.idl`)\nThis IDL file declares the `nsIContentSecurityPolicy` XPCOM interface, defining:\n- CSP directive enumerations (SCRIPT_SRC_DIRECTIVE, STYLE_SRC_DIRECTIVE, etc.)\n- RequireTrustedTypesForDirectiveState enumerations\n- Core methods like `GetPolicy()`, `GetPolicyCount()`, `Permits()`, `GetUpgradeInsecureRequests()`, and `GetBaseURI()`\n\n## Script-src Inline Evaluation\n\nInline script evaluation for script-src is performed in `dom/security/nsCSPUtils.cpp` through the following call chain:\n\n1. `nsCSPContext::ShouldLoad()` - Entry point for content load evaluation\n2. `nsCSPContext::permitsInternal()` - Evaluates permissions against policies\n3. `nsCSPPolicy::permits()` - Checks against the policy\n4. `nsCSPDirective::allows()` - Checks if the directive allows keyword/nonce/hash\n5. `nsCSPBaseSrc::allows()` - Base implementation, overridden by specific source types:\n   - `nsCSPKeywordSrc::allows()` - Handles 'unsafe-inline', 'unsafe-eval', etc.\n   - `nsCSPNonceSrc::allows()` - Handles nonce-based inline script allowance\n   - `nsCSPHashSrc::allows()` - Handles hash-based inline script allowance\n\nThis allows inline scripts to be evaluated based on their nonce or hash values against script-src-elem or script-src directives.\n\n## Violation Reporting\n\nCSP violations are reported through a two-part system:\n- Asynchronous violation reporting via `nsCSPContext::AsyncReportViolation()` which triggers reporting endpoints and observers\n- Inline-specific violation reporting via `nsCSPContext::ReportInlineViolation()` for inline script/style violations\n- Report transmission is handled by `nsCSPContext::SendReports()` and `SendReportsToURIs()`"
